# 1. ArrayList

Dynamic Array.

Example

```java
ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();
```

### Important Methods

```java
list.add(10);

list.add(20);

list.get(1);

list.set(0,100);

list.remove(1);

list.size();

list.contains(100);

list.clear();
```

Example

```java
ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();

list.add(10);

list.add(20);

System.out.println(list);
```

Output

```
[10, 20]
```

Time Complexity

| Operation | Complexity |
|------------|------------|
| add() | O(1) Amortized |
| get() | O(1) |
| set() | O(1) |
| remove(last) | O(1) |
| remove(index) | O(n) |

---

# 2. LinkedList

Implemented as a doubly linked list.

```java
LinkedList<Integer> list = new LinkedList<>();
```

Useful when frequent insertions/deletions are required.

Time Complexity

| Operation | Complexity |
|------------|------------|
| addFirst() | O(1) |
| addLast() | O(1) |
| removeFirst() | O(1) |
| get(index) | O(n) |

---

# ArrayList vs LinkedList

| Feature | ArrayList | LinkedList |
|----------|-----------|------------|
| Random Access | O(1) | O(n) |
| Insert/Delete (Middle) | O(n) | O(1) (after reaching node) |
| Memory | Less | More |
| Preferred in CP | ✅ Yes | Rarely |

---

# 3. Stack

LIFO (Last In First Out)

```java
Stack<Integer> st = new Stack<>();
```

Methods

```java
st.push(10);

st.pop();

st.peek();

st.isEmpty();
```

Example

```java
Stack<Integer> st = new Stack<>();

st.push(1);

st.push(2);

System.out.println(st.pop());
```

Output

```
2
```

Time Complexity

```
Push → O(1)

Pop → O(1)

Peek → O(1)
```

> **Note:** In modern Java, `ArrayDeque` is generally preferred over `Stack` because it is faster and not synchronized.

